WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.820
Hi, I'm Sarah, a data science educator at Posit. In this video, I'll give you a brief

00:00:04.820 --> 00:00:11.060
tour of Positron, Positron's next-generation data science IDE.

00:00:11.060 --> 00:00:15.300
Positron is designed specifically for doing data science. It combines a modern coding

00:00:15.300 --> 00:00:19.660
environment with tools tailored for working with data.

00:00:19.660 --> 00:00:25.020
Positron supports both R and Python, and makes it easy to switch between the languages.

00:00:25.020 --> 00:00:30.340
If you've used RStudio or VSCode, you'll notice some familiar elements. Positron is

00:00:30.340 --> 00:00:36.099
informed by our experience building RStudio, and is a fork of VSCode. You can download

00:00:36.099 --> 00:00:39.540
Positron for Mac, Windows, or Linux on the Positron website.

00:00:39.540 --> 00:00:43.540
Next, let's take a look at some of Positron's key features.

00:00:43.540 --> 00:00:48.619
When you first open up Positron, it will look something like this. The first step is to

00:00:48.619 --> 00:00:55.660
open a folder. You can either open an existing folder, or a new folder. Opening a folder

00:00:55.660 --> 00:01:00.580
will create a workspace and set the working directory, similar to opening up a project

00:01:00.580 --> 00:01:06.339
in RStudio. I'm going to open an existing folder.

00:01:06.339 --> 00:01:11.699
Let's take a look at the layout of Positron. All the way on the left-hand side, the activity

00:01:11.699 --> 00:01:18.419
bar gives access to features like the File Explorer, Positron Assistant, and Extensions.

00:01:18.459 --> 00:01:22.540
The primary sidebar changes depending on what you've selected in the activity bar. So right

00:01:22.540 --> 00:01:27.540
now it's showing our files because we have the File Explorer selected. In the center

00:01:27.540 --> 00:01:32.379
we have the editor where we write our code. At the bottom, you can find the console and

00:01:32.379 --> 00:01:38.180
the terminal. And over on the right-hand side, you have the secondary sidebar. This is where

00:01:38.180 --> 00:01:48.699
plots will show up, where we see our loaded variables, explore database connections, and

00:01:48.699 --> 00:01:51.940
look at documentation.

00:01:51.940 --> 00:01:57.699
Positron supports multiple R and Python interpreters. The active interpreter is shown over here

00:01:57.699 --> 00:02:03.900
in the upper right-hand corner. You can click on the interpreter picker to switch between

00:02:03.900 --> 00:02:09.740
R and Python or between R and Python versions. You'll notice that when I selected R, the

00:02:09.740 --> 00:02:15.699
console is now an R console. You can also switch between languages or versions in the

00:02:15.699 --> 00:02:22.300
console. The active interpreter will be highlighted.

00:02:22.300 --> 00:02:27.300
Loaded variables will show up in the Variables pane on the right-hand side. You can inspect

00:02:27.300 --> 00:02:35.660
variables by expanding them. For data frames, you'll notice this table icon. Clicking on

00:02:35.660 --> 00:02:41.460
that will launch the Data Explorer, which gives you a spreadsheet-style view of the

00:02:41.460 --> 00:02:47.100
data. You can use the Data Explorer to get a high-level overview of your data. You can

00:02:47.100 --> 00:02:55.100
see the distribution of values in each of the columns, as well as filter by condition.

00:02:55.100 --> 00:03:03.100
You can also sort by a column and view missing data percentages and summary statistics, all

00:03:03.100 --> 00:03:04.899
without writing additional code.

00:03:04.899 --> 00:03:11.220
Positron Assistant is an AI tool that provides LLM integration within Positron. You can access

00:03:11.220 --> 00:03:16.699
Positron Assistant from the Activity Bar. Use Positron Assistant to generate code, debug,

00:03:16.699 --> 00:03:23.059
or get suggestions for next steps. Positron Assistant can access context from the Console,

00:03:23.059 --> 00:03:28.380
Variables pane and Plots pane, but you can also manually attach files or folders to

00:03:28.380 --> 00:03:33.580
give it additional context.

00:03:33.580 --> 00:03:39.940
Positron Assistant has three chat modes, Ask, Edit, and Agent. Use Ask mode when you want

00:03:39.940 --> 00:03:52.059
to ask questions, get help with debugging, or use Assistant to generate code.

00:03:52.059 --> 00:03:57.860
For example, we could ask it what we should do next in our analysis of the diamonds data.

00:03:57.860 --> 00:04:09.179
It can reference our Corda document and see what we've already done and suggest next steps.

00:04:09.179 --> 00:04:15.259
On Edit mode, Positron Assistant will suggest code changes.

00:04:15.419 --> 00:04:21.579
So let's say I have another file and I'm getting an error. On Edit mode, I can ask Positron

00:04:21.579 --> 00:04:28.540
Assistant to help fix the problem.

00:04:28.540 --> 00:04:37.660
And notice that it now knows that read diamonds.py is the current file.

00:04:37.660 --> 00:04:46.940
Positron Assistant identifies the issue and supplies a fix that I can accept or undo.

00:04:46.940 --> 00:04:52.179
On Agent mode, Positron Assistant can figure out the next steps needed for your request

00:04:52.179 --> 00:04:57.339
and autonomously carry out those steps. On your behalf, Positron Assistant can execute

00:04:57.339 --> 00:05:02.820
code in the Console, create and modify files, and identify the next steps based on the results

00:05:02.820 --> 00:05:08.820
of the previous steps. For example, we could ask it to move this code that's in read diamonds.py

00:05:08.820 --> 00:05:26.100
into a new Corda file.

00:05:26.100 --> 00:05:32.500
Positron Assistant creates a new Corda document and moves my code over. Note that Positron

00:05:32.500 --> 00:05:36.339
Assistant is currently a preview feature.

00:05:36.339 --> 00:05:41.619
Just like in RStudio, you can pull up documentation for R or Python functions directly within

00:05:41.619 --> 00:05:54.820
the IDE. For either R or Python, you can either use question mark or help. Pull up the documentation

00:05:54.820 --> 00:06:01.619
in the help pane. You can also use the F1 key. This allows you to easily reference

00:06:01.619 --> 00:06:06.739
documentation without leaving Positron. There's a lot more you can do with Positron, but I

00:06:06.739 --> 00:06:11.500
hope this gave you a sense of what's possible. Use the following link to download Positron

00:06:11.500 --> 00:06:12.260
and get started.

